    pearls: ["Shingrix is a NON-LIVE recombinant vaccine and CAN be safely given to immunocompromised patients -- this is a key distinction from the discontinued live Zostavax","Tdap should be given in EVERY pregnancy at 27-32 weeks gestation to maximize passive antibody transfer to the neonate, regardless of prior Tdap history","PCV20 has simplified pneumococcal vaccination -- a single dose replaces the previous sequential PCV13 then PPSV23 regimen for most adults","Live vaccines (MMR, varicella, live attenuated influenza) are contraindicated in pregnancy and in significantly immunocompromised patients","A high HAS-BLED score does not contraindicate vaccination -- it refers to anticoagulation bleeding risk, not vaccination risk; do not confuse clinical scores across conditions","Always ask about egg allergy before influenza vaccination, though current guidelines allow egg-allergic patients to receive any age-appropriate influenza vaccine with standard observation","Vaccine hesitancy is best addressed with motivational interviewing -- acknowledge concerns, provide evidence-based information, and use a presumptive approach ('You are due for your flu shot today')"],
